The early steps introduce classes derived from `Function<dim>` even though that is not actually necessary -- we just call their `value` function, but we never pass such objects around. There is, consequently, no gain in introducing the whole situation.

Worse, in some of these codes, we implement both the `value` and `value_list` function, even though we only ever call one of the two. We then go to great length to explain why we want both and that they need to match -- none of which actually matters, all of which actually confuses students greatly.

I'm going to eventually remove this and just have a regular function of the kind
```
  double coefficient (const Point<dim> &p)
```
or similar. The `Function` object will then only be derived where we actually need it.

We have instances like this:
```
template <typename SparsityPattern>
void make_sparsity_pattern (..., SparsityPattern &sp);
```
Thing is, `SparsityPattern` here is not the name of the class, but just a free template parameter. But that's hardly visible in the doxygen output, and doxygen also links to the documentation of the class (unhelpful). This then confuses readers who see
```
  CompressedSparsityPattern csp;
  make_sparsity_pattern (..., csp);
```
They say that this call shouldn't succeed.

Easy solution: Don't use the name of a class as a template argument's name.
/issues?state=open.title: Don't use the name of classes as template arguments

  - we can provide SolutionTransfer-like support (callback for "interpolation"/"restriction")
  - we can support distributed computations

We have a problem with FEValues and normal vectors:
```
  const Point<spacedim> &normal_vector (const unsigned int i) const;
  const std::vector<Point<spacedim> > &get_normal_vectors () const;
```

The thing is that we use `Point<dim>` in places where we mean a physical point in space, whereas the difference between two points is a `Tensor<1,dim>`. /issues?state=open.body:
Also found by Dakshina Ilangovan:

The documentation of `SchurMatrix` states this:
```
 * Given a non-singular matrix @p A (often positive definite) and a positive
 * semi-definite matrix @p C as well as matrices @p B and @p Dt of full rank,
 * this class implements a new matrix, the Schur complement a the system of
 * equations of the structure
 *
 * @verbatim
 * /        \  /   \     /   \
 * |  A  Dt |  | u |  -  | f |
 * | -B  C  |  | p |  -  | g |
 * \        /  \   /     \   /
 * @endverbatim
 *
 * Multiplication with the Schur matrix @p S is the operation
 * @verbatim
 * S p = C p + B A-inverse Dt-transpose p,
 * @endverbatim
 * which is an operation within the space for @p p.
 *
 * The data handed to the Schur matrix are as follows:
 *
 * @p A: the inverse of @p A is stored, instead of @p A. This allows the
 * application to use the most efficient form of inversion, iterative or
 * direct.
 *
 * @p B, @p C: these matrices are stored "as is".
 *
 * @p Dt: the computation of the Schur complement involves the function @p
 * Tvmult of the matrix @p Dt, not @p vmult! This way, it is sufficient to
 * build only one matrix @p B for the symmetric Schur complement and use it
 * twice.
 *
 * All matrices involved are of arbitrary type and vectors are BlockVectors.
```

This last sentence suggests that the matrices all really just have to have a `vmult/Tvmult` functions plus maybe something that queries their sizes. But in reality, around line 246 of `schur_matrix.h`, there is this code:
```
   h1->reinit(B->n_block_cols(), src.block(0).size());
```
which seems to suggest that the matrices `B` and `Dt` really need to be block matrices themselves. This is consistent with the fact that we multiply with the matrix `B A^{-1} Dt` but the `vmult` operator of this class is
```
  void vmult (BlockVector<double> &dst,
              const BlockVector<double> &src) const;
```
so the Schur complement is apparently expected to have a block structure to itself. 

@guidokanschat : Can you clarify what assumptions you had on the matrix and vector types when you wrote the class? Was your expectation that one would build, say, the Stokes system as a (d+1)x(d+1) block system rather than a 2x2 system?
/issues?state=open.title: Documentation of SchurMatrix is unclear

Dear Devs,

From here: http://www.mcs.anl.gov/petsc/petsc-current/docs/manualpages/Mat/MatCreateAIJ.html One can see that in order to efficiently preallocate a sparse matrix in parallel one has to specify nnz for both diagonal and off-diagonal portion of the matrix. 

Currently, PETScWrappers::MPI::SparseMatrix does not account for this (at least not for all cases) resulting in substantial performance penalty. 

For instance, this method: http://www.dealii.org/8.1.0/doxygen/deal.II/classPETScWrappers_1_1MPI_1_1SparseMatrix.html#aa27a651db22faa0e0d007e209a16f173 creates a matrix in the following way:
ierr = MatCreateAIJ (communicator, local_rows, local_columns, m, n, n_nonzero_per_row, 0, 0, 0, &matrix);

the next line then disables the error message about extra allocations which will happen (because o_nnz is zero above) during matrix assembly:
ierr = MatSetOption (matrix, MAT_NEW_NONZERO_ALLOCATION_ERR, PETSC_FALSE);

I have just hit this issue since my a part of my program slowed down in parallel.
In fact, other (but not all) reinit methods suffer the same issue. 

I would be happy to create a pull request, but I want first to ask which solution you think is better:
1. Simply use n_nonzero_per_row for both diagonal and off-diagonal blocks. This may result in a bigger memory allocation than required
2. Add another parameter to the init methods specifying nnz for diagonal and off-diagonal separately.

Best,
Alexander

_Original issue: http://code.google.com/p/dealii/issues/detail?id=258_
/issues?state=open.title: Inefficient preallocation in PETScWrappers::MPI::SparseMatrix

There are things every program needs at one point or another but that either
- could be precomputed in the background by the object that will eventually have to provide it, or
- could be computed in the background by objects that current compute it as part of their regular constructor.

In either case, the idea is to use available cores early on in the program at a time when they are mostly idle, and already have stuff ready by the time it is necessary. There is a longer discussion on this here: https://groups.google.com/forum/?fromgroups#!topic/dealii-developers/TE5b71IWaLk There was already a patch request (now abandoned) that shows how something like this can be implemented: https://github.com/dealii/dealii/pull/167 Things that could be precomputed:
- locally owned/active/relevant index sets
- some of the stuff we compute in the FE constructors
- possibly constraint matrices

_From [kronbich...@gmail.com](https://code.google.com/u/107881102392393767705/) on September 26, 2014 10:44:50_

Due to the high memory consumption of ConstraintMatrix, it is suggested to improve the storage scheme in the 'close()' call by at least some of the following ideas:
- Detect re-occuring weights between different constraint lines
- Detect when we constrain to the same indices several times (think of Q7 elements in 3D where each of the 4 subfaces constraints to the same 64 indices on the mother faces, with only the weights differing).

Both methods require splitting the storage of weights and indices and invalidates the 'get_constraint_entries' method on the users' side, unfortunately. We might provide an alternative user interface to get a handle on the constraints by creating an iterator to constraints that picks the correct weight/index pair from storage and goes over it; unconstrained indices have begin(line) == end(line). All internal operations like condense(), distribute(), [distribute,add_entries]_local_to_global() should then be done with the iterators instead of the stored compressed data which is likely more complicated to work with. To give users time to adjust their code, we could introduce iterators before the next release (and deprecate get_constraint_entries) and do the actual compression later.

Any other ideas or suggestions?

_Original issue: http://code.google.com/p/dealii/issues/detail?id=256_

_From [florian....@gmail.com](https://code.google.com/u/103174404746239284090/) on July 04, 2014 14:42:12_

In my application I solve a system of equations with solution components u and v on a domain with boundaries A and B. I have Dirichlet values for u on the boundary A and Neumann boundaries on B. For v I have Dirichlet boundaries on both A and B. 

deal.ii doesn't support this use case as the boundary related functions (e.g. VectorTools::interpolate_boundary_values() or MGConstrainedDoFs::initialize()) ask for one FunctionMap and one ComponentMask. This design implies that all components must share the same Dirichlet boundary.

(Sometimes the problem can be circumvented by calling the method in question multiple times, but this is a workaround and doesn't work for e.g. the MGConstrainedDoFs class.)

It would be great if the "boundary functions" would be able to work with objects which can store one ComponentMask per boundary indicator. Either by adding this functionality to the FunctionMap or, to not break existing code, by having e.g. a MaskedFunctionMap object.

_Original issue: http://code.google.com/p/dealii/issues/detail?id=230_
/issues?state=open.title: More flexible FunctionMap with one ComponentMask per boundary indicator
Poor performance for constructor of FE_Nedelec in 3D.

\>> Is this correct? We have previously stored data on either the current cells

_From [bange...@gmail.com](https://code.google.com/u/111126369971033778052/) on May 05, 2014 05:04:41_

METIS can use either 32- or 64-bit indices. This is determined at the top of metis.h which in 64-bit mode looks like this:

\#define METIS_USE_LONGINDEX

\#ifdef METIS_USE_LONGINDEX
\#define IDXTYPEWIDTH 64
\#else
\#define IDXTYPEWIDTH 32
\#endif


Do we need to worry about this? Should we make sure that the index type matches our own types::global_dof_index?

In practice, our code is safe one way or the other. We're also most probably not ever going to be in a situation where we call METIS functions with more than 2B cells/indices. I just ask this question because when we install PETSc and tell it --download-metis, then PETSc configures its sub-METIS with the same index size as PETSc. This leads to awkward situations with our testsuite, as in https://svn.dealii.org/trunk/tests/metis/metis_01a.cc where we can not reliably figure out which output we have to expect if the METIS we happen to use was not obtained from PETSc.

_Original issue: http://code.google.com/p/dealii/issues/detail?id=211_
/issues?state=open.title: Need (?) to check METIS integer size against our own

_From [bange...@gmail.com](https://code.google.com/u/111126369971033778052/) on February 19, 2014 04:45:39_

We have a number of places where we compute the inverse of the mapping F(hat x)=x for a point x in real space, finding the reference coordinates hat x. One of the places is the function that returns whether a point is inside a cell.

We do this in a sort of ad-hoc way that occasionally fails. We should take a look at Damien Lebrun-Grandie's PhD thesis (Texas A&M University, 2014) for some ideas to implement. In particular, I like the rotated bounding box (section 6.2.3) and the good initial guess (section 6.2.2) for the inversion. 

This may make for a simple project for a starting student, if anyone wants to get a student started.

_From [bange...@gmail.com](https://code.google.com/u/111126369971033778052/) on December 25, 2012 16:26:11_

std::auto_ptr has been deprecated in C++11 and we should replace it.

What we should use is unique_ptr. The problem is that we use either the C++11 facilities or the fallback BOOST classes (if the compiler doesn't support C++11 yet) and BOOST doesn't have unique_ptr -- it has scoped_ptr that offers the same functionality but with a different name so it's not trivial to do something like std_cxx1x::unique_ptr.

_Original issue: http://code.google.com/p/dealii/issues/detail?id=3_
/issues?state=open.title: Replace all uses of std::auto_ptr

_From [dr.guido.kanschat](https://code.google.com/u/dr.guido.kanschat/) on September 17, 2012 15:27:07_

For handling of degrees of freedom and most of the structure of finite element data and code, the actual geometry of the mesh is irrelevant.

Therefore, it is suggested to create a class Mesh, which has a minimal comfortable interface to handle mesh topologies and create DoFHandler and similar structures, once the mesh is given.

The current Triangulation class could inherit from Mesh and have the actual functions that fill the mesh class. This way, topology and geometry can still be created by the same refinement functions, if so desired.

The classes of the library that would combine topology and geometry are FEValues and Mapping; in particular, the latter could be more flexible and allow for the exact representation of manifolds

_Original issue: http://code.google.com/p/dealii/issues/detail?id=1_
/issues?state=open.title: Separation of Mesh topology and geometry

/issues?state=open.body:
it is work in progress. In a nutshell, the idea is to wrap shared triangulation into another class and encapsulate all renumbering and distribution of DoFs for the parallel case. So that to the user it behaves similar to the distributed triangulation class. The only exception being that there are no artificial cells (only locally owned and ghost). 

The main modifications are related to policies distribute_dofs and renumber_dofs. 
The ugly thing is that the new NumberCache is returned, whereas the current one 
is provided as a non-const reference to be updated within policy's methods. 
That's because we call DoFRenumbering functions from within the policy class.
I tried to use only NumberCache provided via reference, but there were some issues with the current code in parallel triangulation.

Another family of issues are related to renumbering routines. So far, the same code as in distributed case is used and inside the policy new numbers are gathered among processors. Then sequential renumbering is called and finally NumberCache-related things are updated.

Step 18 was updated to use the class.
/issues?state=open.title: Branch sharedtria
